Bugs Found:
1. Explanation: The AbstractRangeSet class does not handle the case where the input range is null. This can lead to a NullPointerException when calling rangeContaining(null).
   Suggested Fix: public abstract @Nullable Range<C> rangeContaining(@Nullable C value) { if (value == null) { return null; } return rangeContaining(value); }
2. Explanation: The AbstractRangeSet class does not handle the case where the input range is null when calling add(null) or remove(null). This can lead to a NullPointerException.
   Suggested Fix: public void add(@Nullable Range<C> range) { if (range == null) { throw new NullPointerException("Range cannot be null"); } throw new UnsupportedOperationException(); }
3. Explanation: The AbstractRangeSet class does not handle the case where the input range is null when calling removeAll(null). This can lead to a NullPointerException.
   Suggested Fix: public void removeAll(@Nullable Iterable<Range<C>> ranges) { if (ranges == null) { throw new NullPointerException("Ranges cannot be null"); } for (Range<C> range : ranges) { remove(range); } }
4. Explanation: The AbstractRangeSet class does not handle the case where the input range is null when calling removeAll(null). This can lead to a NullPointerException.
   Suggested Fix: public void removeAll(@Nullable RangeSet<C> other) { if (other == null) { throw new NullPointerException("RangeSet cannot be null"); } removeAll(other.asRanges()); }

